1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c4 {This move is one of the more interesting
tries for White. Some lines transpose to Chapter 4 4.Nf3. In 2010 it has been
played by world-class player Nakamura in a blitz game. It has also been played
by Vallejo Pons, Cheparinov and Gawain Jones.} cxd4 5. cxd5 (5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Nxd4
{This transposes to Chapter 4.} (6. Bf4 $6 Bg4 7. Be2 dxc4 $146 8. Bxc4 e6 $17
{[%csl Re5][%cal Gg8e7,Ge7g6,Yg4f3]}) (6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Nc3 {transposes to 5.
cd5.})) (5. Ne2 dxc4 $5 $146 {White's last move gives us this extra option.} (
5... Nc6 6. Nxd4 {transposes to the main line 5.Nf3.}) 6. Nxd4 Qa5+ 7. Nc3
Qxe5+ 8. Be3 {White sacrificed a pawn for quick development and some
initiative.} Nf6 9. Bxc4 e6 10. O-O Be7 11. Qf3 O-O {But once again I don't
see any problems for Black. In the worst case, we will give the material back
by means of ...Nc6 and have an easy play. The position is about equal.}) (5.
Qxd4 {This is the move Nakamura played in the aforementioned blitz game. It's
not the most testing continuation, though. Now we have two sensible options,
the pawn sacrifice 5...Nc6 and the solid 5...e6.} e6 (5... Nc6 6. Qxd5 Bf5 7.
Nf3 e6 8. Qxd8+ Rxd8 $44 {This should be enough compensation for the equality.}
) 6. cxd5 Nc6 7. Bb5 (7. Qa4 exd5 8. Nf3 {Black can easily develop and
equalize.} Bd7 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 9. Bb5 (9. Nc3 $5 {Again White plays for
the initiative.} Nxe5 10. Bb5 Nxf3+ 11. gxf3 a6 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Qxd7+ Kxd7
14. Nxd5 Kc6 15. Nc3 Nf6 $11 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Yb7b6,Gb7b5,Gc6b7]}) 9... Bc5 10.
O-O Nge7 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Ge8g8,Ge7g6] Next move will be 0-0. Black is OK.})
7... Qxd5 8. Qxd5 exd5 9. Nf3 a6 10. Ba4 Bg4 11. O-O Bxf3 $5 $146 12. gxf3
O-O-O {Our pawn structure is better than White's. I prefer Black in this
position.}) 5... Qxd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Nc3 Qd8 8. Nb5 (8. Ne4 $5 $146 {White's
play resembles the Vienna Variation of the QGD.} Bf5 $5 {Forcing the play.
Other good moves are ...Bg4 and ...a6.} 9. Bd3 Qd5 10. Nc3 dxc3 11. Bxf5 Qxd1+
12. Kxd1 e6 13. Be4 Nge7 {White's pair of Bishops compensates for his weakened
pawn structure after dxc3. The position is equal.}) 8... a6 $1 9. Nbxd4 Nxe5 $1
10. Nxe5 Qa5+ 11. b4 Qxe5+ 12. Be2 {At first glance one might think that White
gets a strong initiative for only one pawn. But the following improvement
leads to good play for Black.} Bg4 $1 $146 {Now White has to find a number of
difficult moves to hold the balance.} 13. Be3 $1 (13. f3 Bd7 14. O-O g6 $1 15.
Bb2 Bg7 $17 {[%cal Ge5d6,Gg8f6] Soon Black will complete his development and
enjoy his material advantage.}) 13... Bxe2 14. Kxe2 $1 {Nice idea! White
doesn't care about his King's position and instead goes all in for the
initiative. Now he doesn't need to castle to bring his h1 rook into the game.}
e6 15. Qa4+ $1 {Another important move for White to provoke a weakening of
Black's queenside.} b5 16. Qc2 Ne7 $1 {[%cal Ga8c8]} 17. Rhc1 $1 {The rook on
a1 can be useful for a later a4 push.} Rd8 $1 {[%cal Gd8d4]} 18. Nf3 Qf5 {
White has enough compensation for dynamic equality, but no more than that. 4.
c4 is a critical move in the 3...c5 variation. I suggest you study this
chapter carefully.} *

