1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 {This quiet move is not very popular. Black
can develop his bishop outside the pawn chain and achieve an improved French
Advance.} Nc6 5. Nf3 (5. Ne2 {transposes to 4.Ne2, Chapter 3.}) (5. f4 {
This can not be a good move. White's bishop on c1 doesn't have much of a
future.} cxd4 6. cxd4 Bf5 7. Nc3 e6 8. Nf3 Nge7 9. Be2 Bg4 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge7f5]
Black has an easy game.}) (5. Be2 {White delays the Nf3 move against ...Bg4.}
cxd4 6. cxd4 Bf5 7. Nf3 e6 8. O-O {This is actually a kind of transposition to
another variation in the Caro-Kann Advanced with 3...Bf5 that is not dangerous
for Black. We can reach a good position with simple moves.} Nge7 {The most
logical improvement. Here White has too many options to analyze, so I will
just show a few as a general guideline.} 9. Nc3 (9. Nh4 $2 {leaves the pawn on
d4 unprotected.} Qb6 10. Be3 Qxb2 11. Nd2 Bc2 $1 {A bishop manoeuvre to
remember.} 12. Qc1 Qxc1 13. Rfxc1 Ba4 $1 $146 14. Nb1 Na5 15. Nc3 Bc6 $17 {
Black is a pawn up and has an easy game.}) (9. b3 {This move seems premature
to me. It makes more sense when a Black knight on b6 or a5 threatens to move
to c4. Now Black can go for a different setup.} Ng6 $5 {This position was
played only once. Kindermann continued with} 10. g3 $6 {after which} f6 $5 $146
{attacked the center right away.} 11. exf6 Qxf6 $15 {[%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8] After .
..Bd6 and ...0-0, Black's pieces are very active.}) (9. a3 Nc8 {[%cal Gc8b6,
Gf8e7,Ge8g8] This is simpler and better.} (9... Be4 $5 {I analysed this
interesting move and found it a little bit risky.} 10. Nbd2 (10. Nc3 {This not
dangerous at all.} Nf5 11. Be3 Be7 {Black is OK.}) 10... Nf5 11. b4 a5 12. g4
$1 (12. bxa5 Qxa5 13. g4 Nfxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Nxe4 Nxe2+ 16. Qxe2 dxe4 17.
Qxe4 Bc5 $11) 12... Nfxd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Qa4+ (15. Be3 Nxe2+
16. Qxe2 Qd3 17. Qb2 Be7 18. bxa5 O-O 19. Rfd1 Qa6 20. Rd7 Bd8 $1 $146 {
This keeps Black afloat, but he's still slightly worse.}) 15... Ke7 {Once
again it's not easy to neutralize White's initiative.}) 10. b4 (10. Nbd2 Be7
11. b3 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc4][%cal Yc8b6] A very typical plan when Black's knight
heads to b6.} a5 $5 {Black prepares N8a7 and leaves the b6 square for his
queen.} 12. Bb2 N8a7 13. Re1 O-O 14. Nf1 Rc8 15. Ng3 Bg6 16. Qd2 Qb6 (16... a4
$5 $146 17. b4 Na5 $1 $17 {[%csl Gb3,Gc4][%cal Ga5b3,Gc8c2]}) 17. Bd1 {Black's
play in the following game is very instructive.} Rc7 18. h4 h6 19. Re2 Rfc8 20.
Qf4 Nb8 21. Re3 Nb5 22. Ne2 Nd7 23. Nh2 Rc6 24. Ng4 Qd8 25. Rh3 Qf8 26. a4 Na3
27. Bxa3 Bxa3 28. Rg3 h5 29. Ne3 Bb2 30. Ra2 Bc1 31. Qg5 Qb4 32. Nf4 Bxe3 33.
fxe3 Rc1 34. Nxg6 Rxd1+ 35. Kh2 fxg6 36. Qxg6 Qe7 37. Rf2 Qxh4+ 38. Rh3 Qxf2 {
0-1 Shirov Alexei (2715) - Karpov Anatoly (2740) Las Palmas 1994}) (10. Be3 Be7
{Black keeps the knight on c6 and waits to see how White develops. If White
opts for an early b3, we can choose Karpov's plan ...a5, ...N8a7 and ...Qb6.})
(10. Nc3 Be7 11. Be3 O-O {All positions are more or less the same. Black is OK.
}) (10. Bg5 {White wants to exchange his bad bishop. This doesn't bother us,
as we have our "French bishop" developed outside the pawn chain.} Be7 11. Bxe7
N8xe7 $1 {The bishop White exchanged is called bad because it moved on the
colour of its own central pawns, and was impeded by them. But there's also GM
Mihai Suba's well-known sentence: Bad bishops protect good pawns. The trade
may well be a positional achievement, but at the same time, it becomes more
difficult to protect d4.} 12. Nc3 (12. b4 O-O 13. Nbd2 Qb6 $1 14. Nb3 Rfc8 $1
$146 {[%cal Ga7a5] ...a5 will come next, and it will be difficult for White to
keep the queenside closed.}) 12... Be4 $5 $146 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7f5,Ye4f3]
Black has an easy game.}) 10... Be7 11. Nbd2 Nb6 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Rc1 Rc8 {
Black has no problems. His position may be the more pleasant one already,} 14.
Nb3 Nc4 15. Bxc4 dxc4 16. Rxc4 Qd5 (16... Nxb4 $1 $146 17. Rxc8 Qxc8 18. axb4
Bc2 19. Qa1 Bxb3 {[%csl Gb3] The perfect bishop on d5 provides more than
enough compensation for White's blocked extra pawn.}) 17. Rc3 a5 {0-1 (45)
Hamdouchi, H (2530)-Adams,M (2640) Cap d'Agde 1994}) 9... Nc8 10. Be3 Nb6 11.
a4 $5 {An interesting approach. White grabs some space on the queenside.} Be7 (
11... Nc4 $5 {is also interesting.}) (11... Bb4 {is another option.}) 12. a5
Nc4 $5 {A nice pawn sacrifice.} (12... Nd7 $5 {is also playable.}) 13. Bxc4
dxc4 14. Qa4 O-O {The large number of satisfactory alternatives for Black on
several moves indicates that 4.c3 is not critical.} 15. a6 (15. Qxc4 Nb4 16.
Rfd1 Rc8 17. Qe2 a6 $1 {preparing ...Nd5. Black has nice compensation.} (17...
Nd5 $6 18. Qb5 $14)) 15... Nb4 $15 {1/2 (88)-1/2 (88) Mamedov,N (2588)-Solak,D
(2633) Izmir TUR 2016}) (5. Bb5 {White's idea is to take the knight at some
point and create a weak pawn on c6 and a weak square on c5.} Qa5 $5 {Not
exactly a novelty, but played only twice in rather low-level games. Our idea
is simple: We force White to take on c6 as soon as possible and at the same
time pin the pawn c3 and threaten ...cd4.} (5... Bd7 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc6e5]
This move doesn't work very well here because of} 6. Bxc6 $1 Bxc6 (6... bxc6 {
Maybe the lesser of the two evils, but now 5. ..Bd7 hardly makes sense.}) 7. e6
{This standard pawn sacrifice gives White very good play.}) 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7.
Nd2 cxd4 $5 $146 {Defining the pawn structure.} 8. Nb3 Qb6 9. cxd4 a5 $5 {
Now the Bishop can be developed to a6 or g4, depending on White's play. Later
Black will continue ...e6, ...Ne7 and ...Nf5 with a good position.}) (5. Be3
cxd4 (5... Nh6 {This is the computer's first choice, but I prefer the more
natural and simple text move.}) 6. cxd4 Bf5 {Black achieves easy play with
simple developing moves.} 7. Nc3 e6 {Black can continue ...Nge7, ...Bg6, ...
Nf5 and reach a good position.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 Bg4 (6... Bf5 {is also
possible.}) 7. Be2 (7. Nbd2 e6 8. Be2 Nge7 9. O-O Nf5 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 {
We have reached a position from the 3...Bf5 Advanced Variation which is
already harmless, but here it's even Black to move! This is possible because
our bishop reached g4 in one move here.} Qb6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black has
easy play.}) (7. Be3 e6 8. Be2 Nge7 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7f5,Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Yg4f3,
Yg4h5,Gd8b6] With the usual plans Black achieves a good position again.}) 7...
e6 (7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 e6 9. O-O Qb6 10. Be3 Qxb2 11. Nd2 Bb4 12. Nb3 Qa3 13.
Be2 a6 {is also an interesting option.}) 8. O-O Qb6 9. Nbd2 {White would have
liked to develop his knight to the more active square c3, but this is not
possible due to the pressure on d4.} (9. Be3 Nge7 10. Nbd2 Nf5 {Black has no
problems.}) 9... Nh6 {[%cal Gh6f5,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black has an easy game. His
plan is ...Be7, ...0-0 and ...Nf5 followed by ...f6 or counterplay on the
c-file.} *

