1. e4 c6 2. d4 (2. Ne2 d5 3. e5 c5 4. d4 Nc6 {We can also get the position via
this move order.}) 2... d5 3. e5 c5 4. Ne2 {A strange move which is not that
popular but definitely deserves serious attention. It was played by some
serious names like MVL, Mamedov, or Naiditsch. The idea is to avoid the Bg4
pin.} Nc6 5. c3 {There are no good alternatives for White.} (5. Nbc3 $6 {
This is a tricky move since it is not good to play ...cxd4 directly. In
general, it is not a nice developing move as the knight does not belong on c3
in such structures.} e6 $1 {Now Black threatens to take on e5 after ...cxd4.
As we can see it is difficult to maintain the pawn chain for White whilst
developing in a good manner. Black is already better.} (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nxe5
$2 {If we cannot capture the pawn then there is no sense to take on d4
immediately.} 7. Ndb5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc1f4]}) 6. f4 (6. Be3 Nge7 $146
{[%csl Rd4,Re2,Rf1][%cal Ge7f5]}) 6... Nh6 7. Be3 Nf5 8. Bg1 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nfxd4
10. Bxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bd7 $15 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf8c5]}) (5. f4 {Once again this
is not good on general grounds as the bishop on c1 gets boxed in.} Bg4 6. dxc5
e6 7. Be3 d4 8. Bf2 Bxc5 {Only Black can be better.}) (5. dxc5 e6 {This is a
much better version of 4.dxc5 since the knight on e2 does not make sense.} 6.
Nd4 Nxe5 $146 7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Qe2 Bxb5 9. Qxb5+ Qd7 10. O-O Nf6 $15 {Not only
does Black have the better structure, but the pawn on c5 is also a weakness.})
5... Bf5 6. dxc5 {This is the mainline of the Ne2 variation.} (6. a3 e6 7. b4
cxd4 8. cxd4 (8. Nxd4 Nge7 $1 $146 {is a better move order as this avoids Bf4.}
(8... Bg6 9. Bf4 $5) 9. Bf4 Ng6 10. Bg3 Nxd4 11. cxd4 a6 $15 {[%cal Gf8e7,
Ge8g8,Ga8c8,Yf7f6]}) 8... Nge7 9. Nbc3 Nc8 10. Ng3 Bg6 11. h4 h6 12. h5 Bh7 13.
Be3 Nb6 14. Be2 Rc8 15. Rc1 a5 16. b5 Ne7 17. O-O Nf5 18. Nxf5 Bxf5 19. a4 Nc4
20. Bxc4 Rxc4 21. Nb1 Bb4 22. Nd2 Rxc1 23. Qxc1 O-O 24. Nb3 Bd3 25. Rd1 Be2 26.
Rd2 Bxd2 27. Qxd2 Bxh5 28. Nxa5 Qa8 29. Qb4 Rc8 30. Kh2 Bg6 31. Kg3 Rc2 32. Nb3
Rc4 33. Qe7 Rxa4 34. Nc5 Ra1 35. b6 Rb1 36. Qc7 Kh7 37. Nd7 Rh1 38. Nc5 h5 39.
Nxb7 Qa6 40. f3 Qd3 41. Bf4 h4+ {0-1 (41) Davies,N (2483)-Arkell,K (2521)
Bradford 2002}) (6. Nd2 e6 {We can say that the mission has been accomplished.
Black puts his bishop out of the pawn chain. I do not think any move of White
will change the position much. Let's see one game:} 7. Qa4 Qd7 8. Ng3 Bg6 9.
Nf3 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Ne7 12. Be3 Nc6 13. Bb5 Be7 14. O-O O-O 15. Qd2
a6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. f4 c5 18. Rad1 Rfd8 19. Qf2 Rac8 20. Rd2 Bf8 21. h4 h6 22.
Rfd1 Qe7 23. f5 exf5 24. h5 Bh7 25. Rxd5 Rxd5 26. Rxd5 c4 27. Ra5 Rd8 28. Qe2
Qc7 29. Rxa6 Qxe5 30. Bf2 Qf4 31. Ra5 Qc1+ 32. Kh2 f4 33. Nf5 Rd1 34. Kh3 Rd2
35. Qe1 Qxe1 36. Bxe1 Rxb2 37. Nd4 Be4 38. Nf3 g5 39. hxg6 fxg6 40. Ra4 Bxf3
41. gxf3 Re2 42. Bh4 g5 43. Rxc4 gxh4 44. Rxf4 Rxa2 45. Kxh4 Kg7 46. Rg4+ Kh7
47. Rd4 Kg6 48. Rd5 Ra4+ 49. Rd4 Ra1 50. c4 Rc1 51. Kg3 h5 52. Re4 Bd6+ 53. Kg2
Rc2+ 54. Kf1 Bg3 55. Re2 Rxc4 56. Kg2 Bf4 57. Kh3 Rc1 58. Kg2 Kf5 59. Ra2 Rc8
60. Kh3 Be5 61. Ra4 Rc2 62. f4 Bxf4 63. Ra5+ Be5 {0-1 (63) Narva,T (2065)
-Ehlvest,J (2524) Viljandi EST 2016}) (6. Be3 Qb6 $1 7. Ng3 Bg6 8. Qd2 e6 9.
dxc5 Bxc5 10. Bxc5 Qxc5 11. f4 Nh6 $17) (6. Ng3 Bg6 7. Qb3 (7. e6 fxe6 $146 8.
Bb5 e5 $5 {A practical decision. We have to find a way to develop our kingside
pieces.} 9. dxe5 e6 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gg8e7,Ge7f5,Yg8h6,Yh6f5] Black has no
problems.}) (7. dxc5 e6 8. Be3 Nxe5 9. f4 Nc6 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] The
arising positions will be unclear in general. But I prefer Black because we
have the better pawn structure.}) (7. h4 e6 8. h5 Bxb1 9. Rxb1 cxd4 $1 $146 10.
Bb5 (10. cxd4 Qb6 $17 {[%csl Rd4]}) 10... Nge7 11. O-O a6 12. Bxc6+ Nxc6 13.
cxd4 Qh4 {Black should be OK.}) 7... a6 $5 {Black successfully prevented the
threat of Qb7 due to...Na5. Now White will struggle to justify the position of
the queen.} 8. dxc5 Qc7 (8... Nxe5 $2 9. Qxb7 $16 {As ...Na5 is no longer
possible.}) 9. Qxd5 e6 10. Qc4 Nxe5 11. Qa4+ Nd7 $15 {White is a pawn up but
Black has better coordination. After White's b4 move this pawn will get under
attack with ...a5 and ...b6 at some point and Black will be better.}) 6... Nxe5
$1 {The critical lines start from here.} 7. Nd4 (7. Ng3 $5 {is a very
interesting and rare move.} Bc8 $1 {I know that this is against the chess
rules as we moved our bishop first to f5 and then back to c8 in only 7 moves.
But we exchanged our c-pawn for his e-pawn which is probably favourable for us.
At the same time, however, these two bishop moves should give White some nice
initiative, but the knight on g3 somehow will slow it down.} 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. O-O
e6 10. b4 (10. Be3 Nf6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black is OK.}) 10... g6 $1 11. Be3 (
11. Qd4 $146 {This is more challenging.} Qf6 12. Be3 Qxd4 13. cxd4 a5 14. bxa5
Rxa5 15. a4 Bg7 16. Nd2 Nge7 {Black is OK.}) 11... Bg7 12. Bd4 f6 $5 $146 {
[%cal Gg8e7,Ge6e5]} 13. c4 Nge7 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxc6+ bxc6 16. Nc3 O-O {
Black is OK.}) 7... Bd7 8. Qh5 (8. Nb5 {White is trying to carry out the
obvious Bf4-Nc7 plan. But here we have a very tricky defensive idea.} e6 $1
$146 9. Bf4 Qb8 $1 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Re5d3,Gf8c5]} 10. b4 (10. Qd4 f6 11. Nd2 a6
12. Nd6+ (12. Na3 Ne7 $17 {[%cal Ge7f5]}) 12... Bxd6 13. cxd6 Nc6 14. Qc5 b6
15. Qa3 e5 16. Bg3 Nh6 $15) 10... Nd3+ $15) (8. f4 Nc6 9. Be3 Nf6 10. Nd2 g6
11. Be2 Bh6 $5 $146 {[%cal Ge8g8,Ye7e5] Black will try to push ...e5 at the
right time when Black should be OK.}) (8. Bf4 $6 Ng6 9. Bg3 h5 $5 $146 {
There is some logic behind this pawn push. It will be difficult for White to
decide whether to play h3 or h4. In case of h4, the g4-square will be
available for Black's pieces. And if h3 then I don't see any specific plus for
us. However, I am sure it does not make our position worse than without the ...
h5 push.} 10. h3 (10. h4 e5 11. Nb3 Nf6 $17 {[%csl Rb3,Rc5,Gg4][%cal Ga7a5,
Ga5a4]}) 10... e5 11. Nb3 Nf6 12. N1d2 {There are some options for Black to
play. You can play first Be7, followed by 0-0 and then b6. Before b6 you can
also start with a5. Nearly all options are equally good. The position is
slightly better for Black.}) (8. b4 g6 9. Be2 Bg7 10. O-O e6 $5 $146 (10... Nf6
11. Bf4 Nc6 12. Nd2 {could pose some problems.}) 11. Nd2 (11. Bf4 Ne7 {This is
the idea. Black is okay.}) 11... Nf6 {Black is OK.}) 8... Qb8 $5 {Only 4 games
have been played thus far, but this is the best move in my opinion. Black
tries to maintain the strong position of his knight.} 9. Bf4 (9. f4 $6 {
This move weakens the kingside a lot.} Ng6 10. Qxd5 Nf6 $146 11. Qc4 Nxf4 (
11... e6 {is good enough as well.}) 12. c6 bxc6 13. Nxc6 Qb7 14. Bxf4 Bxc6 {
Black has no problems at all and can already think about more than equality.})
9... Nd3+ 10. Bxd3 Qxf4 11. O-O (11. Ne2 Qc7 $1 $146 12. Qxd5 e6 13. Qg5 Qxc5
$15 {Black has the bishop pair and also easy development.}) (11. Qxd5 $146 {
This move leads to a forced draw, but we need to remember a few lines.} Qc1+
12. Ke2 Qxh1 13. Qxb7 Rd8 14. Bb5 Nf6 15. c6 (15. Nd2 Qxa1 16. c6 Qxa2 17.
cxd7+ (17. c7 Bxb5+ 18. Qxb5+ Nd7 19. cxd8=Q+ Kxd8 20. Qb7 {[%cal Gd4c6]} Nb6
21. Qb8+ Kd7 22. Qb7+ Kd8 23. Qb8+ $11) 17... Nxd7 18. Bxd7+ Rxd7 19. Qc8+ Rd8
20. Qc6+ Rd7 21. Qc8+ Rd8 22. Qc6+ $11) 15... Bg4+ 16. f3 Qxg2+ 17. Ke1 Qg1+
18. Ke2 Qg2+ $11) 11... e6 $5 $146 {The idea is to play ...g6, ...Bg7, and ...
Ne7 in case of White's b4 push.} 12. Re1 (12. b4 g6 $1 13. Qe2 Bg7 {[%cal
Gg8e7,Ge8g8]} 14. Bb5 $5 {White needs to play actively as otherwise he will
have a bad position because of his bad pawn structure and the absence of the
bishop pair.} Qc7 15. Nd2 Ne7 {I prefer Black's chances.}) 12... Bxc5 13. Qxd5
Bxd4 14. Qxd4 (14. cxd4 Bc6 15. Qc5 Rd8 {attacking the d4 pawn immediately.}
16. Bb5 (16. Qxa7 Nf6 $15 {[%csl Rd4]}) 16... Qxd4 17. Bxc6+ bxc6 18. Qxc6+ Qd7
19. Qc5 Ne7 20. Nc3 O-O {Black has no problems}) 14... Qxd4 15. cxd4 Bc6 {
[%cal Gg8f6,Ge8e7,Gh8d8] The position is objectively equal, but Black has the
better structure and can try to play for a win.} *

