1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 e6 5. Bd3 $5 {This is not the main line but
a very tricky one for the Caro-Kann player. We will see the trick in the next
move.} (5. b4 $6 {The attempt of holding on to the pawn will not be crowned
with success.} a5 $1 6. c3 (6. b5 $146 {This is objectively better than
playing 6.c3. But if White has to play 6. b5 after all, why should he weaken
his position with 5.b4 in the first place?!} Bxc5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6] Black
also has a square on b6 for the knight or once again he can go for the ...b6
push with the idea of playing ...Bb7. It is just a good position.}) 6... axb4
7. cxb4 b6 $1 {As we see it is not possible to save the pawn. After the
exchanges, Black will get a better position due to the better pawn structure
and the better piece play. I will not delve deeper here. I believe it is
enough to know it until here. Anyway it is not a critical line.}) (5. c4 Bxc5
6. Nc3 (6. Qg4 $6 Ne7 $1 $146 7. Qxg7 Rg8 8. Qxh7 Qa5+ $1 {This is the
difference compared to other lines where White takes the g7 and h7 pawns. Here
White does not have a good move. Black has the advantage already.} 9. Nd2 (9.
Bd2 Qb6 $19 {[%csl Rb2,Re1,Rf2]}) 9... Nbc6 $17 {[%csl Re1,Rf1,Rg1,Rh1][%cal
Gc8d7] Black has great compensation for the pawns. I am sure Black will get
more in return for his sacrifice.}) 6... Ne7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. cxd5 (8. Bg5 {
This move does not make sense. The bishop is not a strong piece on g5.} Nbc6 {
We continue our development.} 9. Be2 dxc4 $1 $146 {[%csl Re5,Rg5] The pawn on
e5 can be a strong pawn. But in order to have a strong pawn on e5, White
should be able to keep pieces on the board to use his space advantage which is
provided by the pawn on e5. But after a couple of exchanges or through a
disharmony of White's pieces, it can be also a huge weakness. At the same time,
we should remember that this e5-pawn is on the same colour as White's
dark-squared bishop which makes it bad piece more or less.} 10. O-O h6 $5 {
Here the best move of the computer is to take on e7. I am not going to analyze
it. We can take with the queen, then push b6 and play Bb7. Black will have an
easy advantage.} 11. Bf4 (11. Bh4 Qc7 $1 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Ge7f5]} 12. Nb5 Qb6
13. Nd6 Nf5 14. Nxc4 Qc7 $17 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7]}) 11... Nf5 12. Bxc4
b6 $1 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7]}) 8... exd5 9. Bd3 {Here we have two ways to continue.
One is to push ...d4 and to try to use our lead in development. The second way
is to go ...h6, ...Nbc6, ...Ng6 and to try to make use of the e5-pawn in a
classical fashion. It's a matter of taste.} Nbc6 (9... d4 {This is another way
to go.} 10. Ne4 Bb4+ 11. Kf1 Nbc6 12. h4 Qd5 13. Nfg5 Nxe5 14. Qh5 Bf5 15. Nf6+
$8 gxf6 16. Bxf5 Qb5+ 17. Kg1 Nf3+ $8 18. Nxf3 Qxf5 19. Qxf5 Nxf5 20. g4 {
All the knight returns are possible. Black has a bad structure yet the
development advantage will give us the initiative which should lead us to
evaluate the position as balanced.}) 10. O-O h6 {[%cal Ge7g6] Black's play is
simple.} (10... Ng6 $6 11. Bg5 $14 {[%csl Rd5,Rd8] For this reason we need to
play ...h6 before we bring our knight to g6.}) 11. Bf4 Ng6 12. Bxg6 fxg6 13.
Qxd5+ Qxd5 14. Nxd5 Bg4 15. Rac1 b6 $1 {Sooner or later our active pieces will
get the pawn on e5 back.}) 5... Nd7 $1 {I believe this is the strongest
continuation here. Black will play in the spirit of the Advanced Variation of
the French Defense.} (5... Bxc5 $6 6. Qg4 $1 {This was the idea of 5.Bd3,
White wanted to have his queen on the g4-square and that is why he delayed his
Nf3 move. Now White will have an improved version of any variation. This we
should not allow.}) 6. Nf3 Nxc5 7. O-O Ne7 {Here White has tried many moves. I
am not going to analyze them deeply because any of them makes a lot of
difference in the position. The structure is more or less fixed for now. So we
should know how to arrange our pieces. For this reason, I will check a couple
of them. In the end, I don't believe this variation will create any problems
for Black. Still, keep in mind that Vitiugov tried this recently and his
opponent did not know the idea, so White got an excellent position out of the
opening.} 8. Re1 (8. Nbd2 Nc6 9. Nb3 Nxd3 10. cxd3 Be7 $146 {Even after 10...
d4 Black has compensation. I prefer to play in a classical way as I played the
French Defense for a long time and I believe Black does not have any problem.}
(10... d4 {here Agdestein went for this typical move with the idea of ...b7,
and ...Bb7 to activate the light squared bishop. But, at the same time, it
gives the e4-square to White.} 11. Re1 $1 $146 b6 12. Re4 Qd7 13. Nbxd4 Ne7 $1
{[%cal Gc8b7] Black has compensation.})) (8. Nc3 Nxd3 9. Qxd3 Bd7 {1/2-1/2 (29)
Andriasian, Z (2604)-Epishin, V (2563) Villorba 2019}) 8... Nxd3 9. cxd3 {
In this structure, it is well known that White is better because of the space
advantage on the kingside. But to use this space advantage, White should be
able to attack there and it is very difficult to do that without the light
squared bishop. That's the reason I believe Black is OK.} Nc6 10. Nbd2 Be7 11.
Nb3 O-O {Black is fine. You can check the following game:} 12. Bd2 Bd7 13. a3
Rc8 14. Rc1 a5 15. Bc3 b5 16. Nbd4 b4 17. Nxc6 Rxc6 18. axb4 axb4 19. Bd4 Rxc1
