1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 e6 5. Be3 Nd7 6. Bb5 (6. f4 {This has only
been played 4 times. But my friend, the strong grandmaster Durarbayli, used
this move once against a serious opponent which means we should look at this
and learn how to react.} Bxc5 7. Bxc5 Nxc5 8. Nc3 (8. Nf3 Bd7 $5 $146 {[%cal
Ga8c8,Gd8b6,Gg8e7] The position looks easy to play. White has the d4-square
available for his knights but it is not so easy to hold it. I see the engine
lines start with 9.Qd4 which means that Black cannot be worse here, and I
believe it is a very comfortable position.} 9. Qd4 Rc8 {[%cal Gg8e7] This is
the difference between the move 8... Bd7 and 8...Ne7. Black is more than OK.})
8... Bd7 $5 $146 {Once again we play this move first instead of ...Ne7 just to
avoid the Qd4-Qc7 insertion. I believe it is better to be able to play ...Rc8
in order to protect the knight.} 9. Qd4 Rc8 10. Nf3 Ne7 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Kb1
b5 $1 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gb5b4] Black has a very easy game.}) (6. c4 Bxc5 7. Bxc5
Nxc5 8. cxd5 (8. Nc3 Ne7 9. Nf3 (9. Qd4 $2 Qa5 $1 10. b4 Qxb4 11. Rb1 Nc6 12.
Qd2 Ne4 13. Rxb4 Nxd2 14. Ra4 Nxc4 15. Bxc4 dxc4 16. Nf3 Bd7 $19 {Black is
simply a pawn up and also has the bishop.}) 9... Qa5 10. a3 $146 {Maybe this
is the improvement. But still, this variation does not pose problems to Black.}
(10. Be2 Ne4 11. O-O Nxc3 12. bxc3 b6 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge8g8] I prefer
Black.}) (10. Qc2 Ne4 $146 11. Rc1 Bd7 12. cxd5 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 14. Rxc3
Nxd5 {Only Black can be better with the huge d5-square for his pieces.}) 10...
Ne4 11. b4 Nxc3 12. Qc2 Qc7 13. Qxc3 dxc4 14. Qxc4 Qxc4 15. Bxc4 Bd7 {[%cal
Ge8g8,Ge7g6,Ye8e7,Gd7c6] Black is OK.}) 8... exd5 9. Nf3 (9. Qd4 {This move
was played in correspondence game once.} Qa5+ $5 $146 10. b4 Ne6 11. Qd2 Qb6 {
[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8,Gc8d7,Ga7a5] This seems very easy to me. Black is OK.}) 9...
Ne7 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. O-O O-O {Black equalized out of the
opening without many difficulties in 1/2 (84)-1/2 (84) Reshef, O (2482)-Sedlak,
N (2604) Budapest HUN 2018}) (6. Nf3 {This is not the most popular variation,
either. Let's see how to react.} Bxc5 $1 {better than the 6...Ne7 move because
after 7.c4 White strives to get an advantage there.} 7. Bxc5 Nxc5 8. Qd4 {
This is the most popular move in the position. But I believe that if this
should be the best move for White then the whole variation cannot be something
special because the d4-square is certainly not cut out for the queen.} Qb6 9.
Nbd2 Ne7 10. Nb3 Nxb3 $5 11. axb3 Qxd4 12. Nxd4 Ng6 13. Nf3 f6 $5 $146 14. exf6
gxf6 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black is OK.}) 6... Ne7 $5 {There are 26 games in the
database. Once again we go for a rare line. But not just for the sake of
surprising our opponent as this is objectively a better move than the mainline
after 6...Qc7?!} ({The main move} 6... Qc7 $6 {has 89 games in the database.}
7. b4 $1 {and Black will have difficulties to equalize.}) 7. Nf3 (7. c4 $6 {
trying to open up the centre does not make sense here for White because he has
no lead in development. Now Black will get a slight advantage very easily.} Nf5
$1 8. Qd2 $146 (8. cxd5 Nxe3 9. fxe3 Qh4+ 10. g3 Qe4 $17) 8... Nxe3 9. Qxe3
dxc4 10. Nf3 a6 11. Bxc4 Bxc5 $15 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7,Re3e4,Re4a8,Ra8b8] Black
has an easy game.}) (7. b4 {was tried in a correspondence game once.} a6 $5
$146 8. Ba4 $1 (8. Bxd7+ $6 {does not make sense as Black will get the pawn
back.} Bxd7 9. a3 Nf5 10. Nf3 a5 11. Nbd2 Nxe3 12. fxe3 b6 $15) 8... Nf5 $5 (
8... Nc6 {is another way to go} 9. a3 Ndxe5 10. f4 Nc4 11. Bd4 Bd7 12. Bxc6
Bxc6 13. Nf3 b6 $1 {There are some complications yet Black should have enough
play.}) 9. Nf3 Nxe3 10. fxe3 a5 11. c3 g6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf8g7] is an
interesting way to go. Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) (7.
Bxd7+ $6 {is premature.} Bxd7 8. Nf3 Nf5 9. Bd4 Nxd4 $146 10. Qxd4 Rc8 $17) (7.
f4 $6 Nf5 8. Bf2 (8. Qd2 Nxe3 9. Qxe3 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 a6 {Black is already better.
In the game White went wrong very early} 11. Bxd7+ $146 {is better than the
game, but still Black is simply better.} (11. c6 $2 axb5 12. cxd7+ Bxd7 13.
Nge2 b4 14. Nd1 Bc5 15. Nd4 Qb6 16. c3 bxc3 17. bxc3 Ra4 $19) 11... Bxd7 12.
O-O-O Qxc5 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Gc5,Gd7,Gf8][%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4]}) 8... Qa5+ 9. Nc3 a6
{once again White went wrong early in the game} 10. Bxd7+ $146 (10. g4 $2 d4 $1
11. Bxd7+ Bxd7 12. gxf5 dxc3 13. b3 Bc6 $146 14. Nf3 Qb4 $1 $19 {[%cal Gb4e4]})
10... Bxd7 11. Qd2 Bxc5 $17 {[%csl Gc5,Gf5] For a French player this is like a
dream position. Yes, we are playing the Caro-Kann but after 3.dxc5-e6, we are
actually in a French structure.}) (7. c3 a6 $5 $146 {This is a very
interesting move. I want to play in the same spirit as after 7. b4-a6!?N} (7...
Nf5 8. Bd4 {This is the idea of 7.c3}) 8. Bxd7+ (8. Ba4 Nc6 (8... Nf5 $5 9. Bd4
Be7 $1 10. Nf3 O-O 11. Bxd7 Bxd7 12. O-O Qc7 13. b4 a5 14. a3 Nxd4 $1 15. Qxd4
Rfb8 {[%cal Gb7b6] Black has enough play for the pawn.}) 9. b4 Ndxe5 (9... a5
10. f4 axb4 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. cxb4 {Even though the computer shows that Black
has compensation I am not satisfied somehow.}) 10. f4 Nc4 11. Bd4 e5 $5 12.
fxe5 Qh4+ 13. Kf1 $8 a5 14. Nf3 Qf4 15. Kf2 axb4 16. Bxc6+ bxc6 17. cxb4 Bg4 {
Black has very nice compensation for the pawn.}) 8... Bxd7 9. Bd4 Nf5 10. Nf3
Nxd4 11. cxd4 b6 $1 {very classical} 12. cxb6 Qxb6 {[%csl Rb2]} 13. Qb3 Qxb3
14. axb3 Be7 {[%cal Gf7f6,Ge8f7,Gh8b8,Ye8g8,Yf8b8] Black has enough
compensation for the pawn in various ways after this.}) 7... Nf5 (7... a6 $5 {
is also interesting.}) 8. b4 (8. Bd4 Qa5+ 9. Nc3 a6 10. Bxd7+ Bxd7 11. O-O (11.
a3 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qc7 $1 {once again this is a very good French.} 13. f4 $146
Bxc5 14. Qd2 O-O $15) 11... Nxd4 12. Nxd4 (12. Qxd4 Qxc5 $5 $146 {The idea is:}
13. Qg4 Qb4 $1 {Black is better.}) 12... Qxc5 13. Qg4 h5 $5 $146 14. Qf4 g5 $1
15. Qd2 g4 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8,Yf7f6] We will castle queenside and then will look
for a suitable moment for the ...f6 push. Black is slightly better I believe.})
8... a6 $5 $146 9. Ba4 {now this is already a transposition to the 7.b4 line.
Anyway, I will add it here again.} (9. Bg5 f6 $5 (9... Qc7 {is also possible
to go.}) 10. exf6 gxf6 11. Bxd7+ (11. Ne5 h5 {will transpose}) 11... Bxd7 12.
Ne5 h5 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Bxf6 Bg7 15. Bc3 O-O-O {Black has sufficient
compensation.}) 9... Nxe3 10. fxe3 a5 11. c3 g6 $5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf8g7] is
an interesting way to go, actually it is a transposition to 7. b4. Black has
sufficient compensation for the pawn. Let's see some lines from here:} 12. O-O
(12. c6 bxc6 13. Bxc6 Qb6 $5 (13... Ra7 {is a possible continuation.}) 14. Bxa8
Qxe3+ 15. Qe2 Qc1+ 16. Qd1 Qe3+ $11) (12. Nbd2 Qc7 $5 {This is a better move
order than 12...Bg7 in order to avoid the c6 push.} 13. O-O Bg7 14. e4 O-O 15.
exd5 exd5 16. Bxd7 Bxd7 $44) 12... Bh6 $5 13. c6 $1 {White tries to take over
the initiative.} (13. Qd4 O-O 14. a3 axb4 15. Bxd7 Bxd7 16. cxb4 Bg7 $44 {
[%cal Gf7f6]}) 13... bxc6 14. Bxc6 Bxe3+ 15. Kh1 Rb8 16. b5 Bb7 17. c4 Bxc6 18.
bxc6 Nb6 19. Qe1 Bh6 20. cxd5 Nxd5 21. Nc3 O-O $1 22. Rd1 Rc8 $1 {The position
is balanced.} *

