1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 e6 5. Nf3 Bxc5 6. Bd3 (6. a3 Ne7 7. Bd3 (7.
Be2 {That was a try of GM Gledura.} Ng6 8. O-O Nd7 {Now White has to play b4
to protect his pawn on e5. So this will be analyzed in Chapter10.} 9. b4 Be7 {
[%cal Ga7a5]} 10. Bb2 a5 11. b5 O-O $146 {[%cal Gf7f6] Black has no problems.}
(11... Qc7 $146 12. c4 {This was the idea probably.})) 7... Ng6 8. O-O O-O $1 {
transposes to the mainline.}) 6... Ne7 7. O-O Ng6 (7... O-O $4 8. Bxh7+ Kxh7 9.
Ng5+ Kg6 10. h4 $18) 8. a3 (8. Bg5 {This was an interesting attempt by GM
Teske. Now Black has to decide where to place his queen. The move ...Be7 would
not make sense because, in general, it is our good bishop and White's
dark-squared bishop is not a good one. So exchanging those pieces does not
make sense.} Qc7 9. Bxg6 fxg6 $1 {Perfect play by Molinaroli. In case of ...
hxg6, White would have a perfect outpost on g5 for his pieces. By recapturing
with the f-pawn, we have the ...h6 push in order not to allow White to use the
g5-square.} 10. c4 dxc4 11. Nbd2 b5 12. a4 Bb7 13. axb5 O-O $1 $146 {Here is
our improvement.} 14. Qe2 Bd5 $5 (14... Nd7 {is also possible to go.}) 15. Rfc1
Qb6 {I do not believe Black can have a single problem with such a bishop on d5.
}) (8. Re1 Nc6 (8... O-O $5 $146 {In this way Black does not commit his knight
on b8 to c6 directly and waits what White is going to do. This is an
interesting plan. I give you the idea and maybe you can work out the rest
yourself.}) 9. c3 (9. Qe2 O-O 10. Bg5 $6 Nd4 11. Bxd8 Nxe2+ 12. Rxe2 Rxd8 13.
g3 f6 $5 $146 {Black has the bishop pair, so it is time to try opening up the
centre to make use of them.} 14. Bxg6 $5 hxg6 15. h4 b5 $15 {[%cal Gg8f7,Gb5b4,
Gc8d7] Black has a perfect play.}) (9. Be3 Be7 $5 {That's a nice move. As I
mentioned before, in general, we should not allow this exchange.} (9... b6 $5
$146 {This is another move. In this way we can allow White to exchange it
because White will not have the d4-square anymore.}) 10. Bb5 $6 {Not a nice
way to proceed by Fedorov.} O-O $1 $146 {Now White finds it difficult to hold
on to e5. Black is already better.}) (9. a3 $5 {Tricky move order.} a6 $1 $146
{I don't want to start with ...0-0} (9... O-O 10. b4 $1 Bb6 11. Bb2 {This
seems to be slightly better for White.}) (9... a5 $5 $146 {This is another try,
not to allow White to push b4.}) 10. b4 Ba7 11. Bb2 O-O {Now we can see the
difference: Instead of having our bishop on the b6-square we have it on a7
which gives us such pushes like ...b5, ...a5. Furthermore, a move like ...Qb6
to attack f2 is also at our disposal now.} 12. Nbd2 Qb6 $5 13. Rf1 Nf4 $1 {
The bishop on d3 has no squares available.} 14. Nb3 (14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Ng5+
Kg8 16. g3 $1 f6 $1 17. exf6 gxf6 18. gxf4 fxg5 19. Qh5 e5 20. Qg6+ (20. Rae1
d4 21. Qg6+ Kh8 22. Qh6+ Kg8 $11) 20... Kh8 21. Qh6+ Kg8 22. Qg6+ $11 (22.
Qxg5+ $2 Kf7 23. Kh1 Ne7 $1 24. Nf3 Ke8 25. Nxe5 Qf6 $1 $17)) 14... f6 $5 15.
exf6 gxf6 {The position is unclear.}) (9. Nbd2 $6 Qb6 $1 10. Qe2 Nf4 11. Qf1
Nxd3 12. cxd3 Nb4 {Black is already slightly better.}) 9... O-O 10. Be3 Be7 (
10... b6 $5 $146 {possible to go.}) 11. Bd2 f6 $5 $146 12. exf6 Bxf6 {[%cal
Ge6e5]} 13. Qc2 e5 $1 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Qxg6 {Black has enough compensation in
both ways. You can pick one of them.} Ne7 $5 (15... Qb6)) (8. Nbd2 {We should
go for the variation with the exchange sacrifice, and I sincerely advise you
not to forget it.} Nc6 (8... Nf4 $146 9. Nb3 Nxd3 10. cxd3 Be7 11. Be3 {
[%cal Ge3c5]} b6 (11... a5 12. Bc5 Bxc5 13. Nxc5 O-O 14. Rc1 b6 15. Nb3 Nd7 16.
Nbd4 Ba6 {[%csl Rc5,Rd7][%cal Gd8e7,Gf8c8,Ga2a3,Gd1d2,Gb2b4] White has
comfortable play.}) 12. Nbd4 Bb7 13. Qd2 Qd7 14. Rfc1 (14. Bg5 Bc5 $1 {This
should be close to equality after exchanging on d4 and playing ...Nc6.}) 14...
O-O 15. Bg5 {But now it is a different story as we no longer have the move ...
Bc5.} Bxg5 (15... Bc5 $4 {because of the tactical shot} 16. Bf6 $18) 16. Nxg5 {
This will be a pleasure to play with White.}) 9. Nb3 Bb6 10. Re1 (10. Qe2 O-O
11. c4 (11. Bg5 Qc7 12. Bxg6 $146 (12. Rfe1 $6 Ncxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Qxe5
Nxe5 15. Rxe5 f6 16. Bxf6 Rxf6 $15) 12... fxg6 (12... hxg6 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gc7f7,
Gg6g5] also possible to go.}) 13. Rfe1 Bd7 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gg6g5,Gd7e8,Ge8g6]
playable position.}) 11... dxc4 12. Bxg6 $146 {once again both captures are
possible to play} (12. Bxc4 $2 Qc7 13. Re1 Ncxe5 $17 {Black won a healthy pawn.
}) 12... fxg6 {but my feeling tells me that this the better one. I am not
going too deep here because I believe it is easy to play and the position is
balanced.}) 10... O-O 11. Be3 Bc7 $5 $146 {I feel like we are more or less
forced to sacrifice an exchange in order not to have a strategically bad
position by means of exchanging dark-squared bishops.} 12. Bc5 Ncxe5 13. Bxf8
Qxf8 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 {I believe this should provide us with enough counterplay.
We have very nice central pawns and two bishops. I will stop analyzing this
here, and I don't want to go too deeply because from now on every move will be
possible to play.}) (8. Qe2 Nc6 9. c3 {This position can arise from other move
orders as well.} (9. c4 O-O $5 $146 10. Nc3 Qc7 $5 11. Bxg6 (11. cxd5 Ncxe5 12.
Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxe5 Nxe5 $11) 11... fxg6 $1 12. cxd5 exd5 {There are many ways
for White to go, and I will just look at the move} 13. Nxd5 Qf7 14. Qc4 Rd8 15.
Qxc5 Rxd5 16. Qc4 h6 {[%csl Ga8,Gd8,Gf8][%cal Gc8e6,Gg6g5,Ga8d8] Black has
enough play.}) 9... Qc7 {The strong GM Piorun played this lately at the World
Blitz Championship.} (9... O-O {is the main move.}) 10. Re1 f6 $5 $146 {
Here is our new idea.} 11. exf6 (11. b4 Be7 $1 12. exf6 {The only move not to
get a worse position for White. And here both captures are possible to play.}
gxf6 (12... Bxf6 {is also possible, if you don't like the other one you can
analyze this one.}) 13. Na3 (13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. cxd4 Bxb4 15. Bd2 Bxd2 16. Nxd2
O-O {White has some compensation but that's all.}) 13... a6 $1 14. b5 Nce5 15.
Nxe5 Nxe5 16. bxa6 Nxd3 (16... bxa6 17. c4 O-O 18. cxd5 exd5 {Black has a very
bad pawn structure but very nice piece play, and the position is unclear.}) 17.
Qxd3 Rxa6 18. Nb5 Qc6 {This is also unclear.}) 11... gxf6 12. Na3 O-O 13. b4
Bb6 14. Nb5 Qg7 {[%cal Ge6e5] The position is unclear once again, but I like
Black's position with nice central pawns.}) 8... O-O $1 9. Re1 {This was GM
Jakovenko's try in a very important game of the Olympiad against GM Dragun who
showed great chess in that tournament.} (9. g3 {This move is not necessary.
White is preparing b4, Bb2 without allowing Black to play ...Nf4. But, at the
same time, it weakens the f3 knight and if Black will try to open up the
f-file it can create problems for White.} Nc6 10. b4 Be7 $146 11. Bb2 f6 $1 12.
Bxg6 (12. exf6 $2 Bxf6 $17 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gf8f1]}) 12... hxg6 13. Nbd2 g5 {
Black has a comfortable play.}) (9. Nbd2 {This is a very interesting move.
Anand won a beautiful game with it recently} Nc6 10. b4 Bb6 11. Bb2 (11. Bxg6
$5 {This was Anand's novelty. White does not hurry with Bb2 and keeps the idea
of playing Be3 later on.} fxg6 12. Nb3 Bd7 $6 (12... a5 $1 $146 {Black should
hurry with this move.} 13. b5 a4 $1 14. bxc6 (14. Nbd4 $2 Bxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxe5
$17) 14... axb3 $11) 13. Re1 a5 14. b5 Ne7 15. a4 $14 {The computer likes
Black in the beginning, but after careful analysis, I believe that Black's
position is strategically very dangerous.} Rc8 16. Be3 $1 Bxe3 17. Rxe3 Nf5 18.
Rd3 g5 19. h3 b6 20. c4 $3 {A beautiful idea} Rxc4 21. Rxd5 $1 $18 Rf7 22. Rd3
g4 23. Nfd2 Rb4 24. hxg4 Ne7 25. Nf3 Nd5 26. Nbd4 Rf4 27. Nc2 Rbe4 28. Rxd5
exd5 29. Qxd5+ {1-0 (29) Anand,V (2773)-Mamedyarov,S (2817) Wijk aan Zee 2019})
11... Nf4 $1 12. Nb3 f6 $5 $146 {And maybe we can also go for this.} (12... a5
{This is the Vitiugov - Anand game in which Anand had no problems to equalize.}
13. Qd2 Nxd3 14. cxd3 d4 15. bxa5 Bxa5 16. Nxa5 Rxa5 17. Nxd4 Nxe5 18. Rfe1 Rd5
19. Rxe5 Rxe5 20. Nc6 bxc6 21. Bxe5 f6 22. Bc3 c5 23. d4 cxd4 24. Qxd4 Qxd4 25.
Bxd4 Rd8 26. Bb6 Rd6 27. Bc5 Rd5 28. Be3 Bd7 29. h3 Ba4 30. Rc1 Rd1+ 31. Rxd1
Bxd1 32. f3 e5 33. h4 h5 34. Kf2 Kf7 35. Ke1 Ba4 36. Kf2 Bd1 37. Ke1 Ba4 38.
Kf2 {1/2-1/2 (38) Vitiugov,N (2735)-Anand, V (2776) Karlsruhe/Baden Baden GER
2018})) (9. Ng5 {Only 3 games have been played with this tricky move.} Qc7 $1
$146 (9... h6 $4 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. Qh5 $18) (9... Be7 10. Qh5 Bxg5 11. Bxg5 Qc7
12. f4 $1 $146 {This seems to be very dangerous.} (12. Nc3 Qxe5 $1 $146 13.
Rae1 Qd6 $1 14. Re3 Nd7 15. Rh3 h6 16. Bxh6 Nf6 17. Qg5 Nh7 18. Qd2 e5 19. Bxg7
Bxh3 20. Bxf8 Nhxf8 21. gxh3 Rd8 {playable.})) 10. Qh5 h6 11. Nf3 (11. Nxf7
Qxf7 12. Be3 $1 (12. Bxg6 $6 Qxf2+ $3 13. Rxf2 Rxf2 $15 {White cannot keep his
queen on the board, as on the next move Black will take it and will have a
better structure.}) 12... Nf4 $1 13. Qxf7+ Rxf7 14. Bxc5 Nxd3 15. cxd3 Nc6 {
[%csl Re5] It is not easy for White to protect the pawn, and the position is
unclear.} 16. Bd6 b6 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gc8a6,Gc6d4] Black has enough
compensation for the pawn.}) 11... Nc6 12. Re1 (12. b4 $6 {This only weakens
White's position and also gives Black the ...a5 push. Here both options are
possible ...Bb6 and ...Bd4, objectively . ..Bd4 is better.} Bd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 {
[%csl Rc2,Re5]} 14. Be3 (14. f4 Nxc2 15. Ra2 Qb6+ 16. Kh1 Ne3 $17) 14... Nf5 $1
15. Bxf5 exf5 16. Bd4 Nxe5 $15) 12... Nd4 $5 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 14. c3 Bc5 15. a4 $3
{White wants to win the game by means of b4, and we can not retreat our bishop
to e7 because after Bh6 we are losing.} a6 16. Na3 $1 Bd7 17. Nc2 Be8 {[%cal
Gf7f5]} 18. Nd4 Rc8 {The position looks solid. Black has an idea of taking on
d4 with the bishop, followed by Qb6 attacking d4 and then pushing f5. The
position is balanced.} (18... Bxd4 19. cxd4 Qb6 20. Be3 f5 21. exf6 Rxf6 {
[%cal Gg6f4,Re8h5]} 22. Qd1 Qxb2 23. Rb1 Qc3 24. Rxb7 Nf4 {position is
balanced.}) 19. a5 (19. g3 Bxd4 20. cxd4 Qb6 21. Be3 f5 22. exf6 Rxf6 23. Qd1
Ne7 {[%cal Ge8g6] This is once again a French idea.}) 19... Bxd4 $1 20. cxd4
Bb5 $1 21. Bxg6 fxg6 22. Qxg6 Qf7 $1 $11) 9... a6 $5 $146 {That a useful
waiting move. My idea is to prepare ...Nc6. If you would like to have a second
option in this you can check the 9...Nd7 move which was played by GM Dragun.} (
9... Nc6 10. b4 Bb6 11. Bb2 {Now we are in the line I don't recommend.}) (9...
Nd7 {This was Dragun's try. This is also an interesting one. Black should be
okay in both ways. But I want to check my own idea.}) 10. Bg5 $5 (10. Be3 Be7 {
Once again we don't allow this exchange if it's possible.} 11. Nbd2 Nc6 12.
Bxg6 fxg6 13. Nb3 a5 14. Bc5 a4 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Nbd4 Bd7 {Now the scenario
is a little bit different. The f-line is open so Black has enough counterplay,
so we don't need to complain about exchanging dark-squared bishops.}) (10. Bxg6
fxg6 {Opening up the f-line is generally useful for Black. In this way
exchanging dark-squared bishop is not that problematic because we always will
have counterplay on the f-line.} 11. Nbd2 Nc6 12. Nb3 Be7 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gh7h6,
Gc8d7] Black has a comfortable position.}) (10. b4 {This move looks active,
but I think that in some way it weakens the queenside and also gives Black a
clear plan of pushing ...a5.} Be7 $1 {[%cal Ga6a5] Losing a tempo with ...
a6-a5 would not bother me.} 11. Nbd2 a5 12. b5 Nd7 (12... a4 $5 {I could not
understand exactly if this is necessary, but it is interesting.} 13. Bb2 b6 14.
g3 Nd7 15. h4 Nc5 16. h5 Nh8 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gh8f7] interesting position.}) 13. a4
$1 b6 14. Nb3 Bb7 15. Bb2 Re8 $5 16. Bd4 Ngf8 {with the idea ...f5.} 17. Qd2 f5
{The position is balanced, Black should be OK.}) 10... Qc7 (10... Qb6 11. Be3 {
I do not want to allow this with the closed f-file.}) 11. Nbd2 Nc6 12. Nb3 Bb6
{[%csl Re5]} (12... Ba7 {And this is another way to play.} 13. Bxg6 fxg6 14.
Be3 b6 {[%cal Ga7b8,Gh7h6,Ga6a5,Gc8a6,Yd7e8,Yc8d7,Gg6g5,Ye8g6] Looks a little
awkward. The idea is simply to keep the bishop pair on the board. One
important thing is that White has only the d4-square for all his pieces. But
only one piece can stand there. I believe Black has enough play.}) 13. Bxg6
fxg6 14. Be3 Bxe3 15. Rxe3 Bd7 {The position is balanced, the f-file will give
us enough counterplay against the d4 square.} *

